Week 6 Assignment

Individually

Due by Tuesday, 2/28!

Provide feedback on the first iteration of another team’s R markdown file (you’ll be reading the knitted html version). Focus on constructive suggestions for improving the presentation of their measures – visually and narratively – and highlight for them components you think work especially well (and feel free to borrow ideas from one another).

Some elements to consider include: clarity of visualization, alternative or supplemental visuals, framing and language around visuals, framing and language around narrative contextualization, sourcing of information, descriptions, and questions you could imagine other readers asking; but suggestions on any revisions are welcome.

  • Team 1 members review Team 4
  • Team 2 members review Team 5
  • Team 4 members review Team 6
  • Team 5 members review Team 1
  • Team 6 members review Team 2

Submit your feedback (it can be in a document or text copied directly into slack) to the members of the team and to me via direct message in slack.

In Teams

Due by the start of class on 3/2!

Near-final submission of your team’s work:

  1. If you have scripts that prepare your first and second variables that aren’t yet complete, finalize these and share them (and variable three for team 5). If I’ve indicated we should consider a script complete, a version of it may already be up on the github repo.
  2. If you’ve made any additions to the materials I sent for variables three and four, be sure to send the updated scripts for these as well.
  3. Submit your updated R markdown file and knitted html file that presents all of your variables1, including
    1. reads in the prepared data;
    2. visualizes each measure within clearly identified categories/sections (from prior report) and with any useful annotations (e.g., policy changes or events that should be noted to provide context);
    3. provides narrative context each measure following the structure we’ve converged on (using tabs).

Submit these to the stepping stones channel on slack. In our March 2 class, each group will have 10 minutes to walk us through your knitted html file, identify lingering questions, and solicit additional feedback. If suggestions have arisen in the written team feedback (above) or in verbal feedback in class that require implementation in R, I’ll reserve some time to highlight implementation in R. We’ll spend the rest of the time making final revisions or troubleshooting any remaining tricky bits. By the end of class, you’ll post the final R markdown file and knitted html file on slack and I’ll add these to our class webpage along with some prefatory explanation.

  1. Except Team 5, who may still be waiting on the response to the data request to VDH.↩︎
